outlooksByWeek.3: Abdullah has played on only three snaps this season as the Vikings have focused their backfield energies on the one-two punch of Dalvin Cook and Alexander Mattison. Keep the former Lion on waivers at this point.
outlooksByWeek.8: Abdullah did see an uptick in output with Dalvin Cook sidelined in Week 6, but Alexander Mattison handled most of the work and would likely do so again should the starter miss another game. Abdullah does not belong in any fantasy lineups in Week 8.
outlooksByWeek.10: Abdullah scored on his only offensive snap in Week 9, and while the touchdown is great, it's proof that he doesn't belong in your fantasy plans against a tough Chicago defense in Week 10.
outlooksByWeek.14: Abdullah will see a few more carries and touches than usual for a week or two with Alexander Mattison sidelined, but Dalvin Cook is the star of the show in the Minnesota backfield. Abdullah would only be worth a start in fantasy if both Cook and Mattison were out at the same time.
outlooksByWeek.15: With Alexander Mattison out in Week 14, Abdullah played on a decent number of snaps as Minnesota's No. 2 back behind Dalvin Cook. Still, that wasn't enough to elevate him to the level of a start in your fantasy lineup. Even if Mattison remains out, Abdullah is not getting enough touches to be on your squad for this matchup with a tough Bears defense.
outlooksByWeek.16: With Alexander Mattison back, Abdullah hardly saw the field in Week 15. In a top-heavy Vikings' run game, Abdullah is not a fantasy option this week.
outlooksByWeek.17: Abdullah could be in line for a few carries in support of Dalvin Cook in Week 17 if Alexander Mattison remains out. Still, even against a weak Detroit defense, that's not enough to trust Abdullah with a spot in your final lineup of the season.

outlooksByWeek.1: Missing time and missing the end zone held Adams back from the upper echelon of fantasy wideouts in 2019, but his volume and production were still there when he was healthy. His 17.7 points per game total was the second-best of his career and he's still Green Bay's best WR option heading into 2020. The Vikings were among the top-10 most-generous WR fantasy defenses a year ago, so lock in Adams with confidence for Week 1.
outlooksByWeek.2: Adams surprised no one by leading the Packers in targets, receptions and yards in Week 1, ending up as Aaron Rodgers' top target, just like he was for all of last season when healthy. This is the sort of output we should expect from Adams nearly every week and, with the Detroit secondary looking a bit banged up heading into Week 2, the Green Bay receiver is an easy pick as your WR1.
outlooksByWeek.3: Adams suffered a hamstring injury in Week 2 against the Lions, but it appears he avoided a serious setback and could be good to go for Week 3. Keep a close eye on his status, as that will be the only reason you'd keep him out of your fantasy lineup. The Saints were one of the weakest teams against wideouts last season (sixth-most fantasy points allowed to the position) so, despite a solid start to 2020, Adams would still be a must-play here if healthy.
outlooksByWeek.4: Adams has been dealing with a hamstring injury and tweeted this morning that he was not going to be on the field tonight.
outlooksByWeek.6: Keep a close eye on the injury reports this week, because a healthy Adams goes straight into all lineups. The Green Bay offense has been performing well with or without him this season, but he sees such incredible volume and will surely become the focal point of the team once again if he plays. Consider him a top-end WR1 against Tampa Bay, if healthy.
outlooksByWeek.7: Adams was back to seeing double-digit targets in his return to action in Week 6, and while the Packers did struggle mightily against the Buccaneers, it's a positive sign just to see Adams back to full volume. Against a much weaker Houston defense, he's back to being a must-start wideout in what should be a rebound performance for Aaron Rodgers and the Packers.
outlooksByWeek.8: The best receiver in fantasy football was definitely back in action in Week 7, racking up an incredible 196 yards and a pair of scores against a bottom-10 pass defense from Houston. He gets an even better matchup against Minnesota in Week 8 and, while a healthy Aaron Jones could slightly impact his ceiling, that's overthinking it to the highest degree. Adams is arguably the top option in all of fantasy for the week ahead and should start in all leagues.
outlooksByWeek.9: The reception and yardage totals weren't that impressive, but Adams hauled in a trio of TD passes in Week 8 to give him a massive fantasy stat line for the second week in a row. Healthy and back in the lineup since the bye week, Adams has seen double-digit targets in every start and will be even more important in Week 9 against an elite run defense from San Francisco. Look for Adams to be on the receiving end of plenty of Aaron Rodgers' passes, making him one of the top options in all of fantasy this week.
outlooksByWeek.10: Adams delivered a trademark outing against the 49ers in Week 9, racking up 173 yards and scoring a touchdown while logging 12 targets. When healthy this season, Adams has seen double-digit targets and lots of red zone looks. That should continue against one of the weaker pass defenses in the NFL (Jacksonville) in Week 10, when Adams will be a top fantasy wideout in all formats.
outlooksByWeek.11: Adams found the end zone for the fourth straight game in the Packers' Week 10 win over the Jaguars, catching eight passes for 66 yards (including that six-yard scoring strike). Next up is a Colts defense allowing the sixth-fewest WR fantasy points per game. Even so, Adams remains one of the top overall fantasy players and is always a "must start."
outlooksByWeek.12: Adams is one of the best receivers in the NFL and proves that on a weekly basis with incredible stat lines when healthy. Even against a very strong Indianapolis defense in Week 11, he went over 100 yards and found the end zone. The Bears are great against the pass, but nothing should stop you from putting a healthy Adams in your starting lineup.
outlooksByWeek.13: The Packers didn't need to pass the ball all that often iin order to put away the Bears in Week 12, but Adams did find the end zone before the game got too out of hand. That extending his scoring streak to six games and  he'll look to make it seven against the Eagles, a team that's solid against the pass but not too imposing of a matchup. Consider him a top-end WR1 in all leagues in Week 13.
outlooksByWeek.14: Since returning from injury in Week 6, Adams has scored 11 touchdowns over eight games, with 100-plus  yards in four of those contests. He's truly one of the best players in all of fantasy football and should remain locked into your lineups against a lackluster Detroit defense.
outlooksByWeek.15: There may not be a better fantasy player than Adams, who has scored a touchdown in eight straight games with five 100-yard performances over that span. Against a Carolina defense which allowed four passing touchdowns to the Broncos a week ago, lock in Adams as your top wideout and trust that yet another big performance is imminent.
outlooksByWeek.16: Adams did post a disappointing final line in Week 15 against the Panthers, but he still received 10 targets and hauled in seven catches. The Titans provide a much better matchup for opposing wideouts, and it is a perfect spot for a rebound performance from the elite receiver. Trust him as a top wideout in all fantasy formats.
outlooksByWeek.17: Adams made up for a lackluster Week 15 by scoring three times in Week 16's blowout win over the Titans. He's a superstar and a must-play in all formats, even against a much tougher Chicago defense in the 2020 finale.

player.seasonOutlook: Adams is back as Aaron Rodgers' unquestioned No. 1 target -- a role that has allowed him to post four consecutive seasons as a top-10 WR in fantasy points per game. Adams handled a career-high 31% target share and was fantasy's No. 2-scoring WR during the 12 weeks in which he was active last season. He finished as a top-five WR in 42% of those outings, which trailed only Michael Thomas. The only concern here is durability as Adams has missed at least one regular-season game due to injury in each of the past three seasons, including four 2019 absences. We'll need to dock him slightly for that, but the 27-year-old's massive usage locks him into the top-end WR1 mix.

outlooksByWeek.2: Le'Veon Bell's injury afforded Adams work as the team's third-down option in the second half against the Bills last week. While this role netted him a touchdown, it's unlikely Adams consolidates enough touches going forward to factor in fantasy.
outlooksByWeek.3: A busy Week 1 role didn't lead to much exposure in Week 2, with Adams held to just a single touch even with Le'Veon Bell sidelined. With Frank Gore still at the helm of the depth chart, Adams isn't a meaningful option ahead of a meeting with a solid Colts front seven.
outlooksByWeek.13: In Week 12, Adams was active for the first time since Week 2. However, he was also on the field for just one play, a carry that went for a whopping one yard. There's a chance his involvement increases in Week 13 with La'Mical Perine on the IR, but not enough to add him to your fantasy roster.

outlooksByWeek.1: An awesome performance by Agholor in their Super Bowl win for the Eagles was overtaken by a famous meme last season. Now competing for snaps for Las Vegas, the next chapter in Agholor's story begins with a friendly matchup against a thin Carolina secondary. Without a defined role heading into the season, fantasy managers should leave Agholor in free agency for now.
outlooksByWeek.2: Taking over the ceremonial Seth Roberts role which includes averaging nearly one touchdown per catch, Agholor made the most of his single opportunity in Week 1. At sixth in routes run last week, it's tough to get behind the veteran receiver even with the Saints proving somewhat inviting from a statistical lens.
outlooksByWeek.3: A complementary specialist for the Raiders, Agholor played on just 10 routes in Week 2. Without a sizable share of the offense, there's no reason to consider Agholor heading into a tough matchup with the Patriots.
outlooksByWeek.4: The former Philadelphia receiver played a ton with the Raiders' starting tandem of rookies ailing, but the memeable receiver ended up with just 32 yards on 31 routes in the loss. Without real production even when on the field all the time for Las Vegas, it's fine to fade Agholor facing a top secondary this week.
outlooksByWeek.5: Pacing the Raiders with 41 routes run in Week 4, Agholor secured all of his targets and delivered a touchdown in a surprisingly solid showing. There really isn't much to like about his fantasy stock in a bad matchup with a top secondary.
outlooksByWeek.7: With Bryan Edwards getting healthy, Agholor could only see the field in a complementary role for what is a competitive depth chart on Las Vegas. Tampa Bay has allowed 149.5 yards per game to receivers, seventh fewest in the league, leaving Agholor without much fantasy appeal.
outlooksByWeek.8: Roughly 15 air yards per target and attention in the red zone led to a big showing last week for Agholor, who, as Mina Kimes quipped, is the rare person to go to Las Vegas and improve their reputation. With real competition for targets and routes on this receiving depth chart, Agholor tops out as a risky flex in deeper leagues heading into a friendly setup with Cleveland's porous pass defense.
outlooksByWeek.9: Leading the Raiders in routes run this past week, Agholor's role didn't lead to many fantasy points, as he was targeted just twice and finished without a reception. Now that the team's collection of skill players is healthy, Agholor isn't going to see consistent work, it appears. Given this week's unsavory matchup against a solid Chargers secondary, you can find stronger options.
outlooksByWeek.10: A slick one-handed haul from Agholor on a touchdown pass from Derek Carr is likely the highlight of the season for the Las Vegas passing attack thus far. Often found leading the team in routes run each week, Agholor has scored in four of the past five outings, but also enters this game against Denver's porous pass defense with a very low floor.
outlooksByWeek.11: From a one-handed score in Week 9 to just one catch this past week, Agholor's volatility as a fantasy contributor is well established. The Chiefs have allowed the fourth-fewest fantasy points per game to receivers on the season, suggesting it's best to fade Agholor.
outlooksByWeek.12: From a Super Bowl contributor to infamous meme in Philadelphia and now to helpful playmaker for the Raiders, Agholor's shifting status is a reminder that career arcs can prove unpredictable at times. In an offense that likes to spread the ball around, there is real risk in trusting Agholor as a fantasy starter, but at least the matchup is ideal.
outlooksByWeek.13: Second on the Raiders in routes run and third in targets in Week 12, Agholor remains a key part of the Las Vegas passing phase. While there is real risk present in his profile given how this offense prefers to spread the ball around, Agholor does present some streaming potential in deeper leagues given the Jets have allowed 41 fantasy points per game to receiving corps.
outlooksByWeek.14: Able to catch just four of his 11 targets in Week 13, Agholor wasn't able to capitalize on nice usage against a feeble pass defense. This week will prove even more challenging, as the Colts have allowed the 11th-fewest fantasy points to receivers on the season.
outlooksByWeek.15: Delivering his second 100-yard showing of the season this, Agholor has impressively emerged as a viable fantasy play in most formats from the flex spot for this meeting with the Chargers.
outlooksByWeek.16: A breakout season has Agholor earning at least eight targets in four of his past five games, a trend that helps his case a low-end streaming option in deeper PPR leagues. The floor remains low in an offense that relies on running the ball and it's top tight end most often, especially with the Dolphins allowing fewer fantasy points per game to receivers than league average.
outlooksByWeek.17: A breakout season for Las Vegas continued last week for Agholor, as he produced a career-high 155 yards thanks to a career-long 85-yard score in the outing against the Dolphins. Agholor should be in lineups against Denver's injury-plagued cornerbacks in Week 17.

outlooksByWeek.7: The converted cornerback and fantastic special-teams contributor is chipping in at wide receiver for the Lions this season, but not earning enough volume yet to merit a start in fantasy. He has plenty of athleticism and playmaking ability, so do keep an eye on him. Just don't put him in your lineup yet, given his limited opportunities.
outlooksByWeek.8: Agnew is splitting offensive snaps with Marvin Hall and neither is racking up enough playing time or volume to merit consideration, even in incredibly deep leagues. Keep him on waivers for Week 8.
outlooksByWeek.11: In Week 10, Agnew missed his second straight game as a rib injury held him out of the Lions' battle with Washington. He's questionable for this week's visit to Carolina but, even if he does play, Agnew's six catches on the season don't merit a second thought.
outlooksByWeek.12: Agnew hauled in a season-best three passes against the Panthers in Week 11, helping to fill the void for the injured Danny Amendola. The converted defensive back and special-teams ace did not post noteworthy numbers as a receiver and should not be on your fantasy radar.

outlooksByWeek.11: Vaulted into a big role with Myles Gaskin going down, Ahmed was fed the ball throughout Miami's solid home victory in Week 10. The Dolphins appear intent on riding Ahmed as a viable backfield playmaker ahead of this meeting with a Denver defense that was just dominated by the Las Vegas backfield.
outlooksByWeek.12: This past week wasn't pretty for any aspect of the Miami offense, but it's at least encouraging that Ahmed netted 17 touches and was the clear top option from the Dolphins' backfield. Such a rewarding role could convert into a nice fantasy showing this week against a Jets defense that has allowed 26.2 fantasy points per game to receivers.
outlooksByWeek.13: Ahmed's value this week depends on several variables; he is dealing with a shoulder injury that sidelined him this past week and the potential return of Myles Gaskin would alter Ahmed's role if both are active. Which is to say, Ahmed would need to be active and have Gaskin still out in order to have real fantasy value for this sweet matchup with the Bengals. If Gaskin is active, Ahmed is simply a complementary option for Miami.
outlooksByWeek.14: A shoulder injury sidelined Ahmed for the second straight week. Even if he's active this week against the Chiefs, it's likely that Myles Gaskin is only fantasy-relevant option from this backfield.
outlooksByWeek.15: Ahmed is dealing with a shoulder injury that has left him out of multiple games recently, suggesting there is too much risk to deploy him in lineups this week against the Patriots.
outlooksByWeek.16: Averaging a solid 16.7 fantasy points in the three contests he’s earned at least 10 touches this season for the Dolphins, Ahmed enters Week 16 with real potential if Myles Gaskin doesn't return to action, as the Raiders have allowed 4.6 yards per carry and a league-high 23 rushing scores to opponents. If Gaskin is back, Ahmed returns to a change-of-pace role.
outlooksByWeek.17: With Myles Gaskin as the offensive engine for Miami last week, Ahmed, played just 15 snaps and was held to just three yards on seven touches. You can leave Ahmed in free agency for this matchup with the Bills.

outlooksByWeek.1: Aiyuk averaged over 18.0 YPC in his final season at Arizona State and enters the NFL trying to provide San Francisco with a much-needed go-to receiver. He's been nursing a hamstring injury, however, and he plays on an offense focused on running the ball and getting passes to the tight end, so be patient here. Keep him on your bench for now, with an eye towards a strong showing down the road.
outlooksByWeek.2: Aiyuk did not make his NFL debut in Week 1, but could be healthy enough to go in Week 2 against the Jets. If there's going to be a San Francisco wideout worth starting in fantasy this season, it's likely to be Aiyuk, but don't rush to get him into your lineups. The 49ers offense is focused on the tight ends and running backs, so don't expect a ton out of the rookie if he suits up this week.
outlooksByWeek.3: Aiyuk played on a healthy 44 snaps in his debut and hauled in a couple of passes, but he'll need to take a big leap forward and establish himself as a go-to passing-game target before he merits any fantasy consideration. The tight ends and running backs get all the glory in the San Francisco offense, so keep Aiyuk on your bench until he builds rapport with whoever ends up under center.
outlooksByWeek.4: Aiyuk had the first big game of his NFL career in Week 3, going over 100 total yards and scoring a touchdown. There's a chance for him to emerge as the 49ers' top passing-game option outside of the running backs and tight ends. However, in recent seasons, that has proven to be a risky place to be for fantasy purposes. Keep him stashed on your bench for now and out of the lineup for Week 4 against the Eagles.
outlooksByWeek.5: Aiyuk found paydirt in Week 4 for the second game in a row -- this time on a run play. He's playing on a decent number of snaps and finding the end zone, but his volume is too low to consider him for your fantasy lineups just yet. Keep an eye on him in keeper or dynasty leagues, though. He could well become a fantasy mainstay in 2021.
outlooksByWeek.6: Aiyuk has emerged as a regular option in the San Francisco passing game, but this team focuses so heavily on the tight end and running backs that it's hard to trust any of the receivers with a spot in your fantasy lineup. Especially against a Los Angeles team allowing the fewest WR fantasy points per game, Aiyuk should be held out of Week 6 fantasy lineups.
outlooksByWeek.7: In Week 6, Aiyuk found paydirt for the third time this season -- and for the first time on a reception, no less! Still, he does not yet see the volume required to be a viable starter in fantasy. He has tons of potential, but in an offense dominated by tight ends and running backs, the 49ers' No. 2 receiver just isn't a big enough role to earn a spot in your fantasy lineup.
outlooksByWeek.8: With Deebo Samuel ailing and the 49ers' RB situation looking as messy as ever, it could fall to Aiyuk to help fill in the gaps on offense in Week 8. The Seahawks allow a ton of WR fantasy points. Twice this season, the Arizona State product has gone over 100 yards from scrimmage. Assuming Samuel is ruled out, Aiyuk is a WR3/flex pick in all leagues, with a somewhat low floor but also a high ceiling against the porous Seattle secondary.
outlooksByWeek.9: Aiyuk may have emerged as the 49ers' first reliable fantasy option at wideout in quite some time, as he's delivered a pair of great performances in back-to-back outings. However, the 49ers added Aiyuk to the reserve/COVID-19 list, so he won't be able to play in Week 9.
outlooksByWeek.10: Aiyuk has been reinstated from the reserve/COVID-19 list and should be ready to go for Week 10 against the Saints. New Orleans is weaker against the pass than the run and the 49ers have looked to the rookie wideout early and often in his last two starts. With top options George Kittle and Raheem Mostert out, Aiyuk is arguably the best fantasy option in San Francisco and worthy of a start in all formats this week.
outlooksByWeek.12: Aiyuk was placed on the reserve/COVID-19 list while the 49ers were on their bye, and his status for Week 12 is uncertain. Should he start, he'd be a risky flex option  -- and that's only if fellow WR Deebo Samuel remains out. Aiyuk should head to the fantasy bench if his veteran teammate returns.
outlooksByWeek.13: Aiyuk remains on the reserve/COVID-19 list and his status for Week 13 is in doubt. If he's cleared to play, he would line up alongside Deebo Samuel in what would be a rather impressive lineup at receiver for San Francisco and, as such, would be a viable starter in fantasy leagues. Just keep an eye on his status.
outlooksByWeek.14: Aiyuk found the end zone in Week 13, but also dropped a pass that deflected away for an interception. It was a bit of a mixed bag for the rookie, who is competing with Deebo Samuel for looks in a low-upside passing game. Against a very tough Washington defense in Week 14, he's worth a shot as a flex in deeper leagues given his big-play upside.
outlooksByWeek.15: Deebo Samuel is out for the rest of the regular season, opening the door for Aiyuk to serve as the primary playmaker in a struggling 49ers' passing offense. That means his floor is lower than many other top receivers, but his ceiling is high, especially when he's given the share of targets he has in recent appearances. Against a struggling Dallas defense, Aiyuk is a great pick as a WR2 in all formats and leagues.
outlooksByWeek.16: With no Deebo Samuel, Brandon Aiyuk has emerged as the go-to playmaker for the 49ers on offense to close out the season. His fantasy upside for Week 16 depends not on who is under center, but who is at tight end. If George Kittle returns from injury, it will cut into Aiyuk's strong recent volume and target share. That would make him more of a WR3/flex pick. If Kittle remains out, Aiyuk is a borderline WR1 against a weaker Arizona pass defense.
outlooksByWeek.17: Aiyuk has suffered an ankle injury and will not play in Week 17.

player.seasonOutlook: San Francisco selected Aiyuk with the 25th pick of April's draft. Aiyuk comes in at 6-foot, 205 pounds with 4.50 40-yard speed, as well as terrific explosiveness and route-running ability. The Arizona State product's best asset is his post-catch production (10.5 RAC in 2019), which helped him to plenty of big plays at ASU. Aiyuk doesn't have a ton of competition for early-career snaps, but he should be considered a long shot for weekly fantasy value in a super-run-heavy 49ers' offense that will lean heavily on George Kittle and Deebo Samuel. He's worth only a late-round pick.

outlooksByWeek.1: The second-round pick out of Florida State ran for 14 touchdowns in his final season with the Seminoles and caught four more but, with the Rams, he certainly isn't guaranteed the 261 touches he got at the college level. He should factor heavily into his team's RB plans, but Malcolm Brown will get his fair share of snaps, as well. Heading into Week 1, Akers seems like the better fantasy option of the pair, but you should consider him more of a low-end RB2 in his NFL debut.
outlooksByWeek.2: Akers got his fair share of carries in his NFL debut, but couldn't make the most of them, picking up only 39 yards on 14 attempts. Meanwhile, Malcolm Brown had a fantastic day as the starter and appears to be the Rams' top RB option. Akers' playing time was encouraging, but don't pencil him into your starting lineup just yet.
outlooksByWeek.3: Akers suffered a rib injury in Week 2 and might not be fully healthy by the time Week 3's contest with Buffalo rolls around. The rookie was splitting time at running back, anyway, and this likely means he'll take more of a reserve role behind the duo of Malcolm Brown and Darrell Henderson Jr. against the Bills. Keep him on the bench.
outlooksByWeek.4: With Akers sidelined in Week 3, Darrell Henderson Jr. stepped up and provided the Rams with an excellent performance out of the backfield. Looking ahead to Week 4, even if Akers returns, Henderson appears to have claimed the top spot at running back here and is the player to start in fantasy.
outlooksByWeek.5: Akers has missed two straight games and his status for Week 5 is still up in the air. If he returns, he'll join a crowded Rams backfield and likely slot in as the No. 3 option, making him a non-factor in fantasy.
outlooksByWeek.6: Akers made the most of his limited playing time in Week 5, rushing nine times for a team-high 61 yards. That said, with no passing-game involvement and only a few handfuls of snaps each week, he's not reliable enough to place in your starting lineup. This is especially the case against a formidable San Francisco run defense.
outlooksByWeek.7: Akers hardly saw the field in Week 6 against the 49ers while Darrell Henderson Jr. continued to establish himself as the Rams' No. 1 back. Akers is a name to know for dynasty and keeper formats, but for those in redraft leagues, he belongs on the waiver wire due to a lack of playing time.
outlooksByWeek.8: Akers is not in the Rams' offensive gameplan at the moment, with Darrell Henderson Jr. and Malcolm Brown leading the way at running back. The rookie will need to make a move up the depth chart in order to merit a spot on your fantasy squad in anything but a dynasty or keeper league.
outlooksByWeek.10: Akers did handle 10 touches in Week 8, his best total since his debut to start the season. But he's not proven to be a consistent member of the offense and his surge in volume against Miami was partially fueled by Darrell Henderson Jr.'s injury absence. Henderson seems set to return in Week 10, so Akers belongs on the fantasy bench.
outlooksByWeek.11: Akers' involvement in the Los Angeles offense continued to pick up in Week 10 as the rookie carried 10 times for 38 yards. However, he remained a non-entity in the passing game in the Rams' victory over the Seahawks. Despite the added workload, Akers is still in a committee with Malcolm Brown and Darrell Henderson, keeping Akers on the fantasy sideline for Week 11's Monday night game in Tampa Bay.
outlooksByWeek.12: Akers did find the end zone in Week 11 against the Buccaneers -- the first score of his rookie season -- but he's still in a rotation of backs with both Darrell Henderson Jr. and Malcolm Brown. None of these Rams runners stand out enough to merit a start in fantasy, especially with a tough matchup against the 49ers on deck.
outlooksByWeek.13: Yes, Akers has scored in back-to-back games, but he's done so with snap counts hovering in the teens. The Rams are splitting time at running back between three players, so while Akers has looked the best at times in recent weeks, he's yet to launch himself into the lead role and a more fantasy-friendly and dependable status. Keep him on your bench for a potential late-season surge, but don't start him in Week 13 against the Cardinals.
outlooksByWeek.14: Akers surged to the top of the Rams' RB depth chart in Week 13, out-snapping both Darrell Henderson Jr. and Malcolm Brown by a wide margin. He handled 22 touches out of the backfield and scored once, coming up just shy of 100 total yards from scrimmage. The Rams seem set on making Akers their No. 1 back and the focal point of the running game, but he rarely chips in as a receiver. This hurts his fantasy upside a bit, making him more of a flex option (with RB2 upside in deeper leagues) against a strong New England defense.
outlooksByWeek.15: Akers has responded to the challenge of being the top back for the Rams, racking up nearly 200 yards in his second game in a row with more than 20 touches. He's now played on 50-plus snaps in consecutive outings and appears to be in a Todd Gurley-esque role for this offense. That's great news against a struggling Jets defense, making Akers a solid RB1 in all formats.
outlooksByWeek.16: Akers was on track for another solid week of rushing production in Week 15 when an ankle injury sent him to the sidelines. He's been ruled out for Week 16 against Seattle. It will be a mix of Darrell Henderson Jr. and Malcolm Brown stepping up to replace him.
outlooksByWeek.17: Akers suffered an ankle injury in Week 16 and he'll have to play through it in Week 17, if he suits up at all. The Cardinals have a very average run defense, so this would be a fine week to start a healthy Akers. Unfortunately, with his ankle likely still to be in pain and a backup quarterback under center, it might be wise to consider other options -- assuming any are available to you.

player.seasonOutlook: The Rams selected Akers with the 52nd pick of April's draft. The tough and elusive Akers measures in at 5-foot-10, 217 pounds with solid speed (4.47 40-yard dash) and good strength (20 bench reps). Despite lacking some big-play ability and having to do most of his damage after contact last season (5.0 YPC, 1.7 YBC), Akers posted one of the best YAC/forced missed tackle profiles in this year's rookie class. The Florida State product will open his career in a wide-open competition with second-year back Darrell Henderson and Malcolm Brown to replace Todd Gurley. He might not do much as a receiver, but if Akers is able to claim a majority of the carries and goal-line work, he could quickly join the RB2 discussion. Grab him in the middle rounds.

outlooksByWeek.1: Afforded just 55 targets in 16 games last season, Akins lost out on red zone attention to Darren Fells and doesn't enter 2020 with promise for improved usage. The Chiefs struggled against tight ends last season, but Houston simply doesn't rely on the position to move the chains.
outlooksByWeek.2: New season, same role, as Akins led the team's tight ends in routes by a good margin only to end up with two catches and no real red zone role. Without a worthy slice of the offense, Akins won't emerge as a fantasy factor for this tough matchup with the Ravens.
outlooksByWeek.3: A solid showing with seven receptions also included Akins watching Darren Fells vulture yet another touchdown. Either way, Akins isn't in the starting tier of the position this week given both his own lack of scoring pop and this difficult matchup with a proven Pittsburgh pass defense.
outlooksByWeek.4: In his coaching regime in Houston, we've yet to see the Texans deliver a reliable fantasy producer at tight end. Akins ran 25 routes and netted only three targets this past week. The Vikings, meanwhile, have allowed just 11 fantasy points per game to tight ends this season.
outlooksByWeek.5: Week 4 saw Akins leave the game just before the half with a concussion. Clearly a risky option ahead of an otherwise inviting matchup with an exploitable Jaguars defense, Akins isn't worth rostering ahead of this division meeting.
outlooksByWeek.6: Out of the lineup this past week due to a concussion suffered in Week 4, Akins could return to action this week against a Titans defense that struggled to contain tight ends prior to Week 5. Even as the matchup seems appealing, Akins yields important routes and targets to Darren Fells, leaving both of them in free agency in almost all formats.
outlooksByWeek.7: Pharaoh Brown played in place of Akins this past week, but this vet is expected to return to the field for this meeting with the Packers. Given Green Bay's capable back seven and with Darren Fells thriving lately, Akins can be left on the wire.
outlooksByWeek.9: A return from a multi-week injury comes at a good time for Akins in that he nets a matchup with a porous Jacksonville back seven. Then again, Darren Fells has been the better red zone threat for more than a year and Akins hasn't produced many solid statistical outings working with Deshaun Watson. Without much of a track record, you can safely fade Akins.
outlooksByWeek.10: Playing roughly a third of Houston's offensive snaps in his return to action this past week, Akins was eased into the game plan after missing several weeks due to injury. Even with the expectation for more snaps and routes this week, it appears Darren Fells' presence in this offense is enough to cancel any fantasy potential Akins might claim against Cleveland.
outlooksByWeek.11: Once earning the majority of receiving opportunities from the tight end alignment for Houston, the team is now employing a committee approach to the position, evidenced by Akins seeing the same number of routes as Darren Fells in Week 10.
outlooksByWeek.12: In an interesting shift, Akins regained a prominent role in the Houston passing game this past week. Injuries to both Randall Cobb and Kenny Stills likely played a factor in Akins posting his best yardage tally of the year, but it's still encouraging to see him produce. The Lions have yielded just the seventh-fewest fantasy points per game to tight ends, leaving Akins as a risky play.
outlooksByWeek.13: Week 11's big line was likely an outlier, as Akins netted just two targets and zero catches in the team's recent victory over Detroit. Next facing one of the league's best pass defenses, it's wise to fade Akins.
outlooksByWeek.14: The Texans continue to mostly ignore the tight end position in the passing phase, leaving Akins with just two catches despite running 31 routes this past week. The Bears have struggled all season to contain tight ends, but it's quite risky to bet on Akins or any Houston tight end.
outlooksByWeek.15: Even as he finished last week one shy of the team lead in targets, Akins was only able to convert those six looks into 20 yards. Without a major red zone role and next facing a strong pass defense, Akins is an easy fade this week.
outlooksByWeek.16: With a dozen targets across his past two appearances, Akins is finally earning a solid share of the Houston offense. It's unclear if this uptick is a trend or just a recent surge, leaving Akins as a weak play even amid a nice matchup with the Bengals.
outlooksByWeek.17: The Texans deployed three tight ends last week for at least eight routes, with Akins tied with positional peer Pharaoh Brown with 15 in the loss to the Bengals. Sent just four targets in the contest, Akins wasn't able to produce a helpful fantasy outcome. Even with the Titans proving exploitable in coverage, you can find a stronger option than Akins.

outlooksByWeek.1: Not expected to see the field very often with Jack Doyle accustomed to playing heavy snap rates, you should look for stronger sleeper candidates than Alie-Cox at this shallow position.
outlooksByWeek.2: On the field for only 17 routes this past week, Alie-Cox isn't expected to be a steady statistical factor for the Colts' passing game going forward.
outlooksByWeek.3: Entering with a career high of 34 yards, Alie-Cox left Week 2 with the Colts' first 100-yard performance by a tight end since Eric Ebron in 2018. Angling for more snaps in competing with an ailing Jack Doyle, Alie-Cox is an intriguing bench stash given the potential to produce against this low-end Jets back seven.
outlooksByWeek.4: The touchdowns are fun, but it's tough to trust Alie-Cox in lineups until his snap rate leaps; he played just seen routes in Week 3. Game script saw him block a good number of his snaps, but we'll need to see him consume more of an Eric Ebron-like role to become relevant in fantasy for a tough matchup like with the Bears this weekend.
outlooksByWeek.5: Deployed more often as a run blocker than receiving threat this past week, Alie-Cox can't sustain his touchdown pattern given he was third among the team's tight ends in routes in Week 4. Even as the Browns are suspect against the position, leave Alie-Cox in free agency for this one.
outlooksByWeek.6: A knee ailment limited Alie-Cox in Week 5 to just 10 routes and a single target. Then again, he rarely sees much more attention than that in this offense as the team's third option at tight end. With Trey Burton likely entrenched as the top target going forward among the team's trio of tight ends, Alie-Cox shouldn't be near lineups in Week 6.
outlooksByWeek.8: This third-year tight end has 11 catches and nearly 200 yards on the season, so there is clearly some upside present when he touches the ball. Thing is, Alie-Cox can be expected to run third among the team's tight ends in terms of routes and snaps this week. Without enough work, Alie-Cox can't really help fantasy teams in Week 8.
outlooksByWeek.9: The third guy in a two-man platoon at tight end for the Colts, Alie-Cox is merely a complementary player at this stage of the season. The Ravens, meanwhile, have allowed 14 fantasy points per game to tight ends.
outlooksByWeek.10: The timeless question of whether you want more Alie-Cox on your fantasy rosters is upon us. Your answer is likely no, and for good reason; the young tight end is stuck in a limiting committee with Trey Burton often earning more routes and snaps. Even with Jack Doyle ailing and a somewhat inviting matchup up next for this gifted athlete, you can find stronger options (such as Burton) to stream this week.
outlooksByWeek.11: Even as Jack Doyle was ailing this past week, Alie-Cox was limited to four targets and a paltry yardage result in the win. While this athletic tight end can flash as a playmaker at times, a limiting complementary role combined with a matchup against a Packers defense allowing the eighth-fewest yards per game to tight ends keeps him outside the starting fringe.
outlooksByWeek.12: You likely want less Alie-Cox by this stage of the season; he's been dormant as a fantasy option for several weeks and will compete with two established veteran peers at the position this week against the Titans.
outlooksByWeek.13: After several dormant weeks, Alie-Cox appears to be rising into a relevant role again. There still is a defeating share for routes and targets in place with Trey Burton, so Alie-Cox isn't yet worth starting in fantasy lineups, but could make for a fun keeper option given his ascent. The Texans aren't great in coverage, but Alie-Cox would need more work to surface as a fantasy starter.
outlooksByWeek.14: It's somewhat encouraging for his future fantasy value that Alie-Cox has ascended the depth chart to lead his position group in snaps, routes and targets the past few weeks. Less encouraging for his immediate fantasy value is that Trey Burton still looms as a red zone threat and the Raiders, this week's opponent, have been effective in coverage against tight ends.
outlooksByWeek.15: Every few weeks it seems like Alie-Cox flirts with fantasy relevance, but never really emerges as a helpful option. Despite entering Week 14 with a bit of momentum, Alie-Cox was third of the team's trio of tight ends in routes and snaps, confirming he's simply not a trusted fantasy play against the Texans this week.
outlooksByWeek.16: Alie-Cox is now a clear third on the depth chart at tight end and only ran nine routes last week, leaving him without any fantasy value.
outlooksByWeek.17: A distant third among the team's trio of tight ends last week with just seven routes run, this guy simply isn't on the field enough to help fantasy managers in Week 17.

outlooksByWeek.13: Posting just over six fantasy points this past week in an ugly outing against the Giants, Allen shouldn't be near fantasy rosters for this upcoming tilt with a respectable Miami defense.
outlooksByWeek.14: Roughly half of Allen's passing yardage in Week 13 stemmed from a single broken play touchdown in the first quarter. Hit in the pocket throughout the game, Allen left the field after taking his fifth sack in the fourth quarter against Miami, leaving Ryan Finley behind center for Cincinnati. Outside of an early big play on broken coverage to Tyler Boyd, the Bengals averaged 2.5 yards per play on their other 49 offensive snaps. The Cowboys have been porous on defense this season, but there's no reason to look to this passing game for fantasy production.
outlooksByWeek.15: A knee injury saw Allen miss a few snaps last Sunday in a loss to Dallas, but reports suggest he should still be behind center for the Bengals this week against the Steelers. Speaking of Pittsburgh, they claim the league's top pass rush and have yielded the second-fewest fantasy points to passers on the year, leaving Allen as one of the weakest plays at his position this week.
outlooksByWeek.16: Ryan Finley filled in and helped Cincinnati snap a 10-game regular season losing streak to the Steelers. The Bengals didn't ask Finley to do much as a passer with just 13 attempts, but the playbook should open up with Allen behind center against a Houston defense that has struggled against quarterbacks.
outlooksByWeek.17: A career-best passing performance this past week included 371 yards in the air and two scores for Allen. The fantasy fun for Allen might be over, though, as the Ravens' blitz-happy defense is up next, with Baltimore highly motivated to win given playoff implications.

outlooksByWeek.2: An emboldening opener saw Allen become just the third Bills player ever to produce at least 300 yards in the air and 50 on the ground in the same game. With the most rushing scores among quarterbacks since joining the league, maybe Allen can mimic Cam Newton's success against a soft Dolphins defense.
outlooksByWeek.3: Allen is the first Bills quarterback since Jim Kelly to open a season with consecutive 300-yard outings. Even as the Rams have proven solid on defense, Allen's dual-threat skill set earns him another big projection.
outlooksByWeek.4: Fresh from becoming the first player in Bills history to produce at least four passing scores and one rushing score in consecutive games and just the second player in team history with three consecutive 300-yard outings, Allen is set to thrive as a playmaker against a Raiders defense that rates juts 28th in creating pressures per dropback.
outlooksByWeek.5: This surging MVP candidate survived an injury scare to his non-throwing shoulder in Week 4's win. Allen's 12 pass TD through four games ties  Ryan Fitzpatrick from 2012 for the most in franchise history through the first quarter of the season. Allen has completed 72% of his passes thrown at least 10 yards downfield this season, making a massive leap in vertical efficiency from his first two pro campaigns. The Titans present a challenge in that they rank fourth in the league in pressuring passers, but Allen's mobility and downfield creativity supports another QB1 projection.
outlooksByWeek.6: Among the league's most productive vertical passers and always a threat to break a big run scrambling, Allen epitomizes the dual-threat nature of today's top fantasy quarterbacks. One Achilles heel for the Buffalo offense could be allowing a pressure rate around 30% to opponents, especially as this week's opponent, the Chiefs, rate fourth in the league in pressuring quarterbacks.
outlooksByWeek.7: A rough patch these past few weeks against superior AFC opponents saw real regression hit Allen and the Buffalo offense. Then again, his rushing ability helps support a fairly high fantasy floor, while we already know of his stellar statistical ceiling. A nice matchup awaits Allen as he looks to regain early-season form in a meeting with the hapless Jets. New York, after all, rates 21st in pressure rate and is allowing the fifth-most yards per attempt to opponents.
outlooksByWeek.8: Allen amassed strong yardage totals against the Jets, with his season-high 61 rushing yards helping buffer the absence of touchdowns. Next up is a meeting with division rivals out of New England. After struggling earlier in his career against man coverage, Allen is among the best in the league against such schemes this year. Given that the Patriots play man on 65% of opponent dropbacks, second most in the NFL, this should be a revealing matchup of strength-on-strength.
outlooksByWeek.9: After throwing for multiple scores in each of his first five games this season, Allen has failed to do so in consecutive outings. A rushing score helped Allen's case last week, but a return to big passing production could come this week with Seattle among the most generous pass defenses in league history. In an ideal setup for passing output, Allen is among the top plays of the week.
outlooksByWeek.10: Allen became just the first Bills quarterback with multiple regular-season games with at least 400 passing yards and three scores, while franchise legend Jim Kelly had two such games. This dual-threat dynamo next faces an Arizona defense yielding 19 fantasy points per game to signal-callers.
outlooksByWeek.12: Before Buffalo's recent bye week, Allen delivered his fourth-highest fantasy total of the season in an impressive showing against Arizona. Capable of building a big box score via both the run and the pass, Allen is poised for a strong showing against a Chargers defense allowing 20.1 fantasy points per game to quarterbacks, a rate that sits seventh-highest in the NFL.
outlooksByWeek.13: The Chargers' relentless pass rush and strong secondary limited Allen to a modest passing day, but he produced yet another game with a passing and rushing score and now is second only to Cam Newton in games with at least one rush and passing score in his first three seasons. Given his unique dual-threat ability, Allen is positioned as a solid fantasy starter even with the 49ers up next.
outlooksByWeek.14: Allen posted his third game with four passing scores this season to match Jim Kelly (1994) for the most in a single season in Bills history. The Steelers present a real challenge given such a relentless pass rush, but Allen's dual-threat ability and vertical proficiency still support a strong projection.
outlooksByWeek.15: Allen was able to produce QB1 results against the league's top pass rush and a defense allowing the second-fewest fantasy points top passers on the season. Now up to 28 passing scores on the season, Allen is just five shy of Jim Kelly's franchise record. Denver's defensive reputation doesn't fully extend to quarterback production, as they've allowed more than 18 fantasy points per game to signal-callers, supporting a robust projection for Allen this week.
outlooksByWeek.16: Saving his best statistical performance of the season for the heart of the fantasy playoffs, Allen delivered a season-high in fantasy points in helping the Bills secure the team's first division crown since 1995, a year before he was born. Allen became the first Bills player in franchise history with multiple games with two passing and two rushing scores and now sits just three passing scores behind Jim Kelly to tie the franchise record. The Patriots slowed down Allen to his lowest fantasy output of the season back in Week 8, but his recent stretch of production merits trust in all lineups this week.
outlooksByWeek.17: The Bills just swept the season series against the Patriots for first time since 1999 while Allen became the first Bills player in franchise history with four scores and zero interceptions against the Patriots. Already the owner the franchise record for the most passing scores in a season, Allen will look to build on his magical campaign in a meeting with a Miami defense he torched for more than 430 total yards and four scores earlier this season.

player.seasonOutlook: Allen is the perfect example of why rushing is so important when it comes to QB fantasy evaluations. The 2018 first-round pick finished as fantasy's No. 6 QB last season despite ranking 23rd in passing yards, 21st with only 20 passing TDs, third worst in completion percentage (59%) and 11th worst in YPA (6.7). Of course, Allen also produced a 109-510-9 rushing line and has now paced the position in rushing TDs in each of his two NFL seasons (17 total). Allen's passing troubles remain a red flag, but the addition of Stefon Diggs should help his cause. As long as he keeps running, Allen will be a back-end QB1 option.

outlooksByWeek.1: A freshly signed extension should keep Allen with the Chargers for a long time. The target magnet could prove especially busy in Week 1 against a patchwork Bengals secondary with Mike Williams ailing. Expected to earn a huge share of the team's passing offense, Allen enters the season as a high-floor fantasy threat.
outlooksByWeek.2: A forgettable first outing left Allen with just 37 total yards thanks to a modest 68 air yards in the game. The Chiefs don't claim top coverage talents at cornerback, so the hope is that a rewarding rapport between Tyrod Taylor and the newly-paid Allen will surface.
outlooksByWeek.3: A strong, volume-driven showing in Week 2 might prove to be an outlier if the offense reverts to the conservative approach of Tyrod Taylor. Then again, Allen is so consistently open that he can work well with either arm, especially against a subpar secondary such as Carolina's.
outlooksByWeek.4: Eighteen targets is almost certain to deliver special results, with Allen's 13-catch Week 3 opus as evidence. If Justin Herbert remains behind center, this heavy concentration of targets to Allen could continue. The Buccaneers are allowing the 10th fewest yards to receivers, while Allen's rich target share helps offset such matchup woes.
outlooksByWeek.5: Consuming nearly 40% of all the team's targets with Justin Herbert behind center, Allen's awesome market share with the rookie fuels a high fantasy floor. The Saints remain solid against receivers, but Allen's big slice of the pie keeps him in the WR1 club this week.
outlooksByWeek.7: A back injury cut short another potentially impressive outing for Allen shortly after he hauled in a touchdown in Week 5. With Allen enjoying a strong rapport with his rookie passer and with the gifted route-runner likely back in form against a Jacksonville secondary allowing roughly 170 receiving yards per game to wideouts, he's positioned as a solid WR1.
outlooksByWeek.8: It's been quite the boon for Allen's production pattern that Justin Herbert has been the quarterback for much of the season. The vertical work is rewarding and the sheer volume of Allen's target share fuels a really reliable fantasy prospect. The Broncos have allowed nearly 38 fantasy points per game to receiving corps, leaving room for Allen to meet and even surpass his robust projection.
outlooksByWeek.9: Enjoying one of the better workloads in the league and thriving with a daring rookie passer, Allen enters this week's matchup of division rivals with real momentum. The Raiders have been respectable against receivers this season and soft against the run, but Allen's huge share of this offense spells WR1 value for Week 9.
outlooksByWeek.10: Allen delivered yet another strong statistical showing last week, working with sensational rookie passer Justin Herbert. Allen now has three-straight games with at least nine catches and is averaging nearly 13 targets per game working with Herbert this year. Among the safest and most projectable skill players in fantasy this season, Allen next faces a Dolphins secondary allowing nearly 40 fantasy points per game to receiving corps.
outlooksByWeek.11: A touchdown helped save an otherwise inefficient outing for Allen this past Sunday, as he was only able to secure 43% of his targets. The good news is that we can project another strong workload for Allen amid a friendly matchup with a Jets secondary allowing 40.3 fantasy points per game to receivers
outlooksByWeek.12: A career high in receptions for this target magnet in Week 11 certainly helped his fantasy investors. With Justin Herbert thriving of late and Allen positioned as the clear top target for the Chargers, he's a solid WR1 candidate for this tilt with the Bills.
outlooksByWeek.13: Despite throwing a touchdown to Allen this past Sunday, Justin Herbert had a hard time getting the ball to him throughout the loss to Buffalo, completing just four of his 10 attempts to the Pro Bowl wideout, the lowest catch percentage for Allen with Herbert as his starting QB. Entering this week, Herbert and Allen had connected on 77 receptions, the most in the league by a duo this season. Given the larger sample of success, even facing a solid set of New England corners isn't enough to slow down this impressive passing battery.
outlooksByWeek.14: An ugly outing overall for the Chargers' offense left Allen with a modest line despite pacing the team with 11 targets. A sluggish catch rate against a Patriots defense that playing at a high level this past week is likely just a matchup-driven outcome, as Allen next faces a porous Atlanta pass defense. Given such an awesome share of the Chargers' passing game, Allen makes for a strong play this week.
outlooksByWeek.15: Having just posted his sixth game of the year with at least 20 fantasy points in ESPN PPR formats, Allen has been among the most consistent fantasy forces at his position this year. A hamstring injury seemed to have limited his snap count against the Falcons, so it's worth following this injury throughout the week, but Allen is in a great spot to produce if active this week against a suspect pass defense.
outlooksByWeek.16: A hamstring limited Allen to just 12 routes and three targets in a disappointing outing for the proven veteran wideout. The target magnet would need to be a better spot health-wise to produce a strong line in Week 16, but it does help his case as a fantasy starter that he produced nine catches and a touchdown against the Broncos earlier this year.
outlooksByWeek.17: A week removed from trying to hit the field despite a lingering hamstring injury, Allen didn't play this past Sunday against the Falcons. If Allen is closer to full capacity this week, then he could help fantasy investors given his awesome blend of route running and target volume against what should be the Chiefs' backups.

player.seasonOutlook: Allen enters his eighth NFL season in unfamiliar territory. The 2013 third-round pick has been targeted 758 times in his career -- and 751 of them have come from the hand of Philip Rivers. Rivers, who is now with the Colts, has helped Allen to top-13 finishes in targets, receptions, receiving yards and fantasy points in each of the past three seasons. Even with Rivers, Allen is coming off a very boom/bust fantasy campaign in which he was a top-20 WR in half of his outings, but outside the top 30 during the other half. Allen is still in his prime at age 28 and hasn't missed a game since 2016, but he hasn't scored more than six TDs in any season since 2013. The uncertainty of the Chargers' quarterback situation is a red flag, so Allen is best viewed as a WR2.

outlooksByWeek.2: Allen begins the season as the backup to Dwayne Haskins, largely due to his familiarity with offensive coordinator Scott Turner’s system. That said, Alex Smith looms and could ultimately usurp No. 2 quarterback duties as he continues to work his way back from 2018’s horrific leg injury. Even if Allen were to see action, there isn’t ample offensive support in Washington for him to be a fantasy option.
outlooksByWeek.6: Allen got the Week 5 start after Dwayne Haskins Jr. was demoted to third string and wasn't even active for the contest. However, Allen was subsequently forced out of the game after taking a hard hit to his non-throwing arm. Ron Rivera has announced that Allen will return as soon as he's ready, which is likely this week against the Giants. Regardless, Allen hasn't yet proven himself to be a fantasy starter.
outlooksByWeek.7: After being forced out of his first start of the season in Week 5 with an injury to his non-throwing arm, Allen was back under center in Wek 6, coming up just short as Washington fell to the Giants 20-19. Allen was effective, throwing for 280 yards and a pair of scores, though he did turn the ball over twice, including a fumble returned for a touchdown. Sunday's effort was enough to earn Allen the Week 7 start against a vulnerable Cowboys defense. However, he still shouldn't be trusted to anchor a fantasy lineup just yet.
outlooksByWeek.9: Allen emerges from the Week 8 bye on a TD roll, having thrown a pair of scored in both of the two games heading into Washington's bye week. After defeating the Cowboys in Week 7, Washington has another NFC East matchup on tap, with the Giants visiting on Sunday night. While Allen is settling in as Washington's starter, his production still falls well short of being fantasy-worthy.
outlooksByWeek.10: Allen season's came to a premature end as he underwent surgery to repair a fractured left ankle incurred Week 9 against the Giants.

outlooksByWeek.1: Amendola went over 100 yards three times last season, but finished with 30-or-fewer yards on seven occasions. The veteran receiver is more than capable of delivering a big performance, but the inconsistency makes him tough to trust for your fantasy lineup. This is especially true against a formidable Bears defense. Keep him sidelined in Week 1.
outlooksByWeek.2: Amendola's usage in the passing game has been tough to predict since he arrived in Detroit. In Week 1, he did see an unsurprising uptick in opportunities with Kenny Golladay out. Should Golladay return for Week 2, it would be wise to keep Amendola on the bench in fantasy, as his targets should decrease from the seven he saw against Chicago. However, if Golladay remains out, Amendola is a worthy flex flier against a Green Bay defense that stumbled in Week 1.
outlooksByWeek.3: Amendola has stepped into a bigger role in the Lions offense with Kenny Golladay out, but it hasn't translated into any of the huge performances he delivered a season ago. Instead, he has only seven receptions over two games and stands to lose some chances to Golladay should he return in Week 3. Steer clear of Amendola in anything but the deepest of leagues.
outlooksByWeek.6: Amendola made a pair of nice catches in Week 4 against the Saints, but that's not enough to merit a start in fantasy. Matthew Stafford is spreading the ball around in the Lions' passing game, and Kenny Golladay is the only one seeing the sort of volume needed to be a starter in fantasy. Keep Amendola benched against Jacksonville.
outlooksByWeek.7: Amendola has caught five total passes since Kenny Golladay returned to action after grabbing five receptions in Week 1 when Golladay was out. The veteran is a viable fantasy option when provided the chance to step into a bigger role for Detroit, but as the No. 3 option in the Lions' passing game, he doesn't see the ball enough to merit a spot in your fantasy lineup -- not even against a weak Atlanta defense.
outlooksByWeek.8: Amendola is great at popping up with appealing stat lines every now and then, only to fade into obscurity almost immediately after. His latest effort was decent -- 62 yards on three receptions against Atlanta -- but now he and the Lions face a much tougher Indianapolis defense in Week 8. Keep him on the fantasy sidelines for this one.
outlooksByWeek.9: Amendola tends to pop up and deliver big numbers whenever another Detroit wideout is injured, but so far this season we've yet to see a truly breakout performance from the veteran in those situations. With Kenny Golladay likely out for Week 9 and a matchup with a porous Minnesota defense on tap, it's tempting to consider Amendola for your lineups. That said, with Marvin Hall playing well in Golladay's place last week, we could see Amendola remain third-in-line for opportunities at receiver, which means he's not a viable fantasy starter.
outlooksByWeek.10: Amendola stepped up to fill the void left by the injured Kenny Golladay in Week 9, catching 7 of 10 targets for his best PPR point total of the season. He has yet to find the end zone in 2020, however, and will not be a viable fantasy option if Golladay returns. But if the Lions' top receiver remains out, Amendola is worthy of a flex spot in deeper leagues for Week 10, even against a tough Washington defense.
outlooksByWeek.11: A hip injury forced Amendola out of the second half of the Lions' Week 10 game versus Washington. The veteran was unable to return and begins Week 11 as questionable for Detroit's encounter with Carolina. Even if he plays, Amendola's production isn't consistent enough to be trusted for fantasy purposes.
outlooksByWeek.12: Amendola was sidelined in Week 11, leaving the Lions fairly thin at receiver. If he's able to return and Kenny Golladay does not, he could have a decent outing as  Detroit's No. 2 receiver, but his track record this season suggests he's best left on the bench.
outlooksByWeek.13: Amendola has not played in two weeks. Should he return in Week 13, he'll face a tough Chicago defense and will likely take the field alongside a healthier, deeper Detroit receiving corps than the one we saw against Houston on Thanksgiving. That means Amendola would be back to the part-time role that hasn't produced many fantasy-friendly performances this season. Keep him on the bench for this one.
outlooksByWeek.14: Amendola returned to action in Week 13 but didn't make the most of his opportunity to shine while Kenny Golladay was out. He managed only three catches (on five targets) and has not really had the sort of breakout game this season that he's been known in recent years to produce. That's enough reason to keep him out of your lineup this week against a tough Green Bay secondary.
outlooksByWeek.15: The veteran Amendola is splitting time with Mohamed Sanu, among others, to cover for the injured Kenny Golladay. While in the past, Amendola has delivered some solid outings when given an elevated status due to injuries around him on the depth chart, this season he's struggled to get anything going. His Week 14 performance was solid, but there's not enough proof that he's a consistent target in the Detroit offense. Simply put, he can't be trusted with a valuable starting spot in your Week 15 lineup -- not even against a bad Tennessee secondary.
outlooksByWeek.16: Amendola is splitting time as the No. 3 wideout for the Lions with Quintez Cephus, lagging behind Mohamed Sanu Sr. and Marvin Jones Jr. -- even with Kenny Golladay out. There's just not enough offense available for the veteran. He's not a viable fantasy option.
outlooksByWeek.17: Amendola got the opportunities in Week 16 but, like most of the Detroit offense, failed to get anything going against the Buccaneers. He's unlikely to see another seven targets against the Vikings in Week 17, and even if he does, there's no track record to suggest that would be worth a spot in your fantasy lineup.

player.seasonOutlook: Amendola re-upped with the Lions and returns as Matthew Stafford's primary slot target. Though Amendola's 78 targets barely trailed Marvin Jones (86) and Kenny Golladay (85) during the 12 games the trio played together last season, he wasn't anywhere near the fantasy contributor that his counterparts proved to be. The culprits were a heavy dosage of short-area targets (8.6 aDOT, 6.9 YPT) and the usual lack of touchdowns (1 TD, 2 end-zone targets). Amendola has been around since 2008, but has never cleared four touchdowns in a single season. The 34-year-old also hasn't finished any season better than WR43 in fantasy since 2010. He's well off the fantasy radar.

outlooksByWeek.1: Anderson was fun to watch during his time with the Jets, as his top-end speed was among the best in the NFL despite a less-than-ideal QB situation during his tenure there. He'll now join Teddy Bridgewater in Carolina and he'll be helped by lining up with D.J. Moore on the other side of the field. That said, Anderson has yet to prove to be a consistent fantasy option, and is no more than a flex flier until he takes the next step with his new team.
outlooksByWeek.2: Anderson’s first game with his new team was a success, fueled by a 75-yard TD catch, one of six receptions for 115 yards. Anderson is athletic and capable of making big plays. Just don’t expect the same level of production each week, beginning with a Week 2 meeting with an improved Tampa Bay unit. That said, the Buccaneers secondary is young and susceptible to deep threats, so Anderson checks in as a WR3/flex option.
outlooksByWeek.3: In Week 2, Anderson eclipsed the century mark in receiving yards for the second straight week, only one fewer time than all of last season. He'll be hard-pressed to make it three straight weeks facing a Chargers secondary that was able to hold Tyreek Hill to only 99 yards last week. Anderson's early success merits flex consideration, but don't get used to this level of production.
outlooksByWeek.4: After eclipsing the century mark in both of the first two games, Anderson registered only 55 yards on five catches in Week 3. Still, Anderson led Panthers wideouts with six targets and has established himself as a presence on his new team. With a decent floor and big-play ability, Anderson has earned WR3/flex status.
outlooksByWeek.5: Anderson rebounded from last week's mediocre performance, barely missing the century mark with 99 yards receiving. It would have been the third time for Anderson to surpass the 100-yard plateau. Anderson has yet to score, but that could change this week as the Panthers visit Atlanta, whose secondary has allowed the most TD catches in the league. Anderson's production over the first quarter of the season places him as a strong WR2 in Week 5.
outlooksByWeek.6: After logging an average depth of target of over 15 yards with the Jets in his first two seasons in the league, Anderson is now running much shorter routes -- with great success. He's reached triple-digit receiving yards three times, including last Sunday's 112 yard effort, which came on eight catches. The Bears have a good pass defense, but Anderson's new-found prowess underneath should keep him as a WR2.
outlooksByWeek.7: Anderson has been mostly working underneath since joining Carolina. In Week 6, he shook free for a couple of long gains against the Bears, catching four balls for 77 yards, good for a season-high 19.3 yards per reception. This week, Anderson faces a Saints secondary that has been victimized for 15 WR touchdowns in five games. All of this lands Anderson as a solid fantasy WR2 for Week 7.
outlooksByWeek.8: Anderson continues to be one of the most reliable wide receivers in the game, catching another six balls for 74 yards in Week 7. As a testament to his solid campaign, the yardage total was his second-lowest of the season. Anderson is in a great position for another productive week, facing a Falcons secondary which has allowed the second-most passing yards and WR touchdowns per game.
outlooksByWeek.9: After eclipsing 50 yards in each of the Panthers' first seven games, Anderson fell two yards short in Week 8 as the Falcons defense held him to an average of 9.6 YPC on his five grabs. Week 9 brings a Chiefs secondary allowing the third-fewest points to opposing wideouts. Still, Anderson has emerged as Teddy Bridgewater's favorite target so he should be busy, especially since Carolina will likely be forced to throw to keep up with Kansas City's beefy offense.
outlooksByWeek.10: Anderson was targeted a season-high 13 times, catching nine for 63 yards in Carolina's Week 9 loss in Kansas City. Sunday brings a Week 2 rematch with the Buccaneers where Anderson also reeled in nine balls, totaling 109 yards. Anderson may have snuck up on Tampa Bay last time but even if they're ready for him, he's Teddy Bridgewater's favorite wideout and should continue to put up WR1/WR2 numbers.
outlooksByWeek.11: Anderson registered his lowest output of the season in the Panthers' Week 10 loss to the Buccaneers, corralling just four balls for a season-low 21 yards. Expect a more typical showing this week at home against the Lions. Anderson remains a solid every-week fantasy start.
outlooksByWeek.12: Anderson wasn't fazed as P.J. Walker took snaps in Week 11 in the place of an injured Teddy Bridgewater. In fact, he hauled in seven balls for 46 yards in the Panthers' win over the Lions. Anderson has at least four catches in every game with Week 11's 46 yards being his second-lowest yardage total of the season. Anderson is in line for another productive effort when the Panthers draw the Vikings' vulnerable secondary in a Week 12 road affair.
outlooksByWeek.14: When the Panthers last played in Week 12, Anderson tallied his second TD pass of the season -- his first score since Week 1. Carolina resumes their schedule with a Week 14 visit from Denver. The Broncos have yielded the eighth-fewest WR fantasy points per game, but Anderson has established a target floor worthy of being started every week. Just temper your expectations to that of WR3 territory.
outlooksByWeek.15: With eight catches for 96 yards in Week 14, Anderson added onto his career-high catch total while setting a new personal best with 996 receiving yards. Next up is a Saturday date with the Packers to kickoff the Week 15 slate. Anderson remains an every-week start and should eclipse the 1,000-yard plateau for the first time in his career, despite facing a Green Bay secondary allowing the fifth-fewest WR fantasy points.
outlooksByWeek.16: After establishing himself as one of the steadiest wideouts in the league, Week 15 was Anderson's first true dud of 2020 as he managed just two catches for 21 yards in the Panthers' loss to Green Bay. Week 16 presents a challenge against a stout Washington secondary, but Anderson remains a borderline top-20 option at the WR position.
outlooksByWeek.17: Anderson only compiled 39 receiving yards in Week 16, but he caught seven balls -- including one for a score. The former Jet will look to close out his first campaign with the Panthers on a high note when Carolina hosts New Orleans in Week 17. The Saints defense is stingy to wideouts, but Anderson's heavy weekly involvement in Carolina's offense warrants a spot in your fantasy lineup.

player.seasonOutlook: Following four seasons with the Jets, Anderson signed with Carolina during the offseason. Anderson went undrafted in 2016, but went on to appear in 62 of 64 games with New York, hauling in 206 passes for 3,034 yards and 20 touchdowns. Anderson was limited to one strong fantasy campaign (18th in 2017) and finished 39th and 40th in the past two seasons. In Anderson's defense, a position-high 33% of balls thrown his direction were 'off target' last season. In Carolina, the 26-year-old vertical threat will work alongside DJ Moore and Curtis Samuel in Matt Rhule's new-look offense led by QB Teddy Bridgewater. Consistency is unlikely with Christian McCaffrey as the focal point of the Panthers' offense, so Anderson is safest as a borderline flex play in deeper leagues.

outlooksByWeek.1: A breakout 2019 effort saw Andrews overcome a modest snap rate by consuming a dominant share of the Baltimore passing offense. Now that there is less competition for snaps and routes with Hayden Hurst down in Atlanta, Andrews is positioned as a solid starting fantasy force heading into this opening matchup with a Cleveland team that allowed tight ends to haul in 68% of their targets last season.
outlooksByWeek.2: In just his third NFL appearance with at least 42 snaps, Andrews thrived as the unquestioned lead tight end after serving in more of a committee approach last year. You can't expect multi-score outings each week from Andrews, but facing a weaker Houston back seven that has allowed the most yards per game to tight ends since Week 10 of last year results in a healthy projection.
outlooksByWeek.3: Lamar Jackson didn't push the ball outside in Week 2 and instead kept the ball underneath in a conservative showing. Andrews was limited to just one haul, but is expected to prove busy in a higher-scoring affair with the Chiefs. Kansas City has been solid in coverage, but volume and red zone attention both work in Andrews' favor.
outlooksByWeek.4: Close to a much bigger game this past Monday with a few missed connections down the seam and in the red zone. Andrews' rough Week 3 seems more like an outlier than trend. The Washington Football Team, meanwhile, has allowed just over 57 yards per game to tight ends, setting up Andrews for a solid showing.
outlooksByWeek.5: Turning three targets into two touchdowns and nearly 60 yards was quite the feat of efficiency from Andrews this past week. Now third in team history in multi-score games, Andrews should thrive against a generous Cincinnati defense allowing 65 receiving yards per game to tight ends.
outlooksByWeek.6: Both Marquise Brown and Andrews enjoyed rewarding 27% target shares this past Sunday. Even as the receiving pie can prove small some weeks given Baltimore's propensity to run, Andrews' consistently valuable share of total targets and red zone looks aids his case as a top fantasy option. It also helps Andrews' fantasy profile this week that the Eagles have allowed a generous 18.6 fantasy points per game to tight ends on the year, fourth most in the league.
outlooksByWeek.8: A run-heavy approach against the Eagles a few weeks back saw Nick Boyle on the field more than Andrews, making for a forgettable fantasy outing. Given his great red zone pedigree, Andrews is still among the best weekly threats to score a receiving touchdown in the league. That fuels a solid projection for this meeting with Pittsburgh, a defense that has surrendered the seventh-fewest fantasy points to tight ends.
outlooksByWeek.9: While Andrews nearly evenly split snaps with Nick Boyle in this recent loss to the Steelers, he was far busier as a receiving threat in leading the team with six targets. The Steelers' back seven were successful in slowing down Andrews in the outing, while the Colts are up next and have actually allowed the fewest fantasy points per game to the position this season. Still a starting option for fantasy managers, expectations are to be tempered given the caliber of defensive opponent.
outlooksByWeek.10: A strong start the season has since seen Andrews struggle to produce meaningful statistical results the past several weeks; the hulking tight end hasn't topped 32 yards since Week 5. With the Patriots playing so much man coverage, it's still possible Andrews can win some one-on-one matchups and deliver TE1 value in Week 10 against a Patriots defense that has allowed the second-fewest fantasy points per game to tight ends.
outlooksByWeek.11: With Nick Boyle suffering a serious injury the team's recent loss, Andrews is expected to play a much higher snap rate going forward. After all, this gifted pass-catcher netted season highs in receptions and yards this past week. With the Titans struggling in coverage thus far this season, Andrews makes for a solid fantasy starter this week.
outlooksByWeek.12: The recent injury to Nick Boyle has had a real influence on Andrews' opportunity rates the past two weeks; he just delivered a season-high in yardage in Week 11 and has posted at least five catches in consecutive games for the first time this season.
outlooksByWeek.13: Andrews missed Week 12's tilt with the rival Steelers due to a positive COVID-19 result, placing his status for Week 13's matchup with the Cowboys in doubt. If he's active in time for this inviting matchup with one of the leagues' weakest pass defenses, Andrews would be a top option at his position.
outlooksByWeek.14: Activated and able to participate in practice, Andrews is looking for this next matchup with the Browns. Cleveland, per the matchup metrics, has surrendered the second-most fantasy points to tight ends on the season. The floor might be a bit low given the struggles this passing game has endured, but Andrews' ceiling is quite high.
outlooksByWeek.15: Second only to Travis Kelce among tight ends in receiving plays of at least 20 yards since the start of last season, Andrews remains a dangerous playmaker even as the Baltimore passing game has struggled. The Jaguars present a soft matchup for Andrews to exploit, setting him up as a strong play at this fickle position.
outlooksByWeek.16: This past Sunday, Lamar Jackson and Andrews connected for their 17th touchdown working together, only trailing Patrick Mahomes and Travis Kelce (23) for the most scores by a QB-TE combo since Jackson’s debut in 2018. Without the fun target volume that drives Kelce's elite yardage output, Andrews is decidedly more dependent on touchdown production, but at least he's a top target in his offense and faces a Giants team that is right around league average in defending tight ends.
outlooksByWeek.17: A season-high 11 targets for Andrews in Week 16 helped drive a solid yardage outcome for the talented tight end against the Giants. Back in Week 5 against the Bengals, Andrews delivered a touchdown and six catches, evidence he can thrive again this week.

player.seasonOutlook: A 2018 third-round pick, Andrews exited his rookie campaign seemingly set to become one of the league's next great tight ends. It's fair to say he delivered the goods in 2019. Despite ranking 40th at the position in snaps, Andrews handled a massive 25% target share for Baltimore's league-best offense en route to a TE5 fantasy campaign. Andrews' 11 end zone targets tied for most among tight ends and eighth in the entire league. That helped him to 10 touchdowns. Andrews' has ranked no lower than fifth in aDOT or YPR during his two pro seasons. Lamar Jackson's top target enters his age-24 season as a solid TE1 option.

outlooksByWeek.1: Arcega-Whiteside has a big opportunity in Week 1, as Alshon Jeffrey and Jalen Reagor are both likely out, leaving the second-year pro with a starter's spot if he can claim it in practice. However, with two passing-game capable running backs and two good tight ends, Carson Wentz has plenty of options to consider on offense, and Arcega-Whiteside has yet to develop a connection with his quarterback. He's best left on the fantasy bench for this one.
outlooksByWeek.2: Arcega-Whiteside was in on 28 snaps but didn’t receive a single target. He's far down on the Eagles' WR depth chart, and this is  a team that incorporates two tight ends into the regular gameplan. This doesn’t bode well for Arcega-Whiteside’s fantasy production this season. It certainly won't be good in Week 2.
