outlooksByWeek.4: Arcega-Whiteside incurred a lower body injury prior to last Sunday's contest with the Bengals but was still active, though he rarely played and was not targeted. If healthy, Arcega-Whiteside could see significant action thanks to the fact that Alshon Jeffery, DeSean Jackson, and Jalen Reagor are all nursing injuries. Still, it's not enough to trust for fantasy purposes.
outlooksByWeek.5: A sore calf kept Arcega-Whiteside from competing last week, further depleting an already banged-up Eagles' receiving corps. He'll try to suit up this week, but even if he does, Arcega-Whiteside won't be a fantasy factor facing the Steelers defense.
outlooksByWeek.6: After missing Week 4 with a sore calf, Arcega-Whiteside drew the starting assignment against the Steelers but still ran only five routes. He ended up catching just one ball, albeit for 37 yards. There's no reason to believe Arcega-Whiteside will produce at a fantasy-worthy level in Week 6 when the Ravens pay a visit to the City of Brotherly Love.
outlooksByWeek.8: Arcega-Whiteside was one of nine Eagles to log a reception last week, handling his only target for eight yards. Considering it was just his second catch of the season, Arcega-Whiteside has no fantasy utility.

player.seasonOutlook: Arcega-Whiteside is back for his second NFL season following an underwhelming rookie campaign. Injuries above him on the depth chart should have positioned the 2019 second-round pick for a generous offensive workload, but instead he was held to 21 targets and a 10-169-1 receiving line on 463 snaps. Clearly not pleased with his progress, the Eagles drafted Jalen Reagor, John Hightower and Quez Watkins, while also acquiring Marquise Goodwin during draft weekend. Given that there's already Alshon Jeffery, DeSean Jackson and Greg Ward in the fold and Arcega-Whiteside has a very tough path to a second-year breakout. He should be rostered only in dynasty leagues or those very rare "Eagles-only" formats.

outlooksByWeek.2: Armah will see the occasional goal-line carry, as he did in Week 1 -- though he failed to convert the effort. He’ll continue to be the lead blocker for Christian McCaffrey, but there’s no equivalent of "rushing yard assists" in fantasy football scoring.
outlooksByWeek.5: Armah got one carry for two yards in Week 4. His primary role for the Panthers remains as a blocker in two-back sets.
outlooksByWeek.6: Even with a shorthanded backfield in Week 5, Armah was called upon for just one carry and no pass targets. He continues to be a non-factor.
outlooksByWeek.7: Armah still hasn't caught a pass this season, failing to connect with Teddy Bridgewater on his only Week 6 look. The fullback also didn't get a single carry this time around, after having toted the rock just once in each of the prior two games.
outlooksByWeek.11: Armah caught a pair of passes in Week 10, but lost five yards in the process. Ouch! His primary role continues to be as a lead blocker in short-yardage scenarios.
outlooksByWeek.12: In Week 11, Armah played on 13 offensive snaps. It was his highest total since Week 4, but he still only saw a single unsuccessful target with no carries. He remains a fantasy non-entity.
outlooksByWeek.15: Armah hauled in a rare target in Week 14, making it four catches on the season for the fullback.
outlooksByWeek.17: Week 16 afforded Armah just one touch, which resulted in a 3-yard carry. His primary duties for the Panthers remain as a blocking back and on special teams.

outlooksByWeek.1: Leonard Fournette, accounted for 30.6% of team’s 2019 scrimmage yards, while Armstead and Chris Thompson combined for just 246 rushing yards last season. Arguably the top candidate to handle early-down duties now that Fournette is with Tampa Bay, Armstead is a worthy stash to consider ahead of a meeting with a Colts defense that allowed the 10th-fewest rushing yards to backs last season.

player.seasonOutlook: Armstead enters his second professional season competing for lead back duties following the August release of Leonard Fournette. The 2019 fifth-round pick produced 108 yards on 35 carries (3.1 YPC, 1.9 YAC) and 144 yards and a pair of touchdowns on 24 targets (6.0 YPT) off the bench as a rookie. Armstead will certainly defer passing-down work to Chris Thompson, but could emerge as a flex if he fends off Devin Ozigbo (among others) for primary ball-carrier duties. He's a fine mid-round flier.

outlooksByWeek.1: The TE position was not a productive one for the Cardinals a year ago, but Arnold was the lone bright spot, acquired in December and immediately given a big opportunity in this offense. He hauled in a pair of touchdowns over the final three weeks, but still figures to be in a battle with Maxx Williams for looks in the passing game. Wait and see how this situation pans out before plugging any Arizona tight end into your lineup.
outlooksByWeek.2: Arnold matched Maxx Williams in terms of both snaps and targets in Week 1, but he was able to haul in his looks in the passing game while Williams was shut out. However, even if you combined the volume and production of the two Arizona tight ends, it wouldn't be good enough for fantasy. This position has proven to be one to avoid in the Kliff Kingsbury era.
outlooksByWeek.3: Arnold managed only two receptions on four targets as the Cardinals' primary tight end in Week 2 with Maxx Williams sidelined. Under head coach Kliff Kingsbury, the Cardinals have not provided their tight ends with a lot of opportunities in the passing game, so it's best to avoid Arnold for Week 3 against Detroit.
outlooksByWeek.4: The TE position has not offered fantasy options in Arizona since Kliff Kingsbury arrived, and that remains true in 2020. Arnold has only eight targets through three weeks, and is not involved with the offense in the red zone. Keep him on waivers or the bench for Week 4.
outlooksByWeek.5: Arnold did see an uptick in volume in Week 4 with a season-high four receptions, but that's still not enough to earn a start in fantasy leagues. The Cardinals simply do not utilize the tight end enough to consider Arnold for your starting lineup.
outlooksByWeek.6: Arnold fell behind Darrell Daniels in terms of playing time last week, meaning his fantasy relevance is virtually non-existent. The Cardinals have not utilized the TE position in their passing game often enough to consider either player as a starter for Week 6 against Dallas.
outlooksByWeek.7: Arnold has seen his playing time drop over the past two weeks, with Darrell Daniels taking over the starting spot for the Cardinals and Arnold barely seeing the field. He was the target of a pass that was nullified by a penalty, but he didn't otherwise get involved in the Arizona offense in Week 6. He doesn't belong in any Week 7 lineups.
outlooksByWeek.9: Arnold had his best outing of the season heading into Arizona's bye week, racking up 57 yards against Seattle, but that came on only three targets. The tight ends are simply not utilized often enough in the Cardinals offense to even begin to consider Arnold for your Week 9 lineups.
outlooksByWeek.10: Arnold saw the field on a season-low 18 snaps in Week 9 with Maxx Williams back in action, and at this point it seems he's third on the depth chart at the position and unlikely to see that many targets per game. He's not a recommended fantasy option for Week 10 against Buffalo.
outlooksByWeek.11: Arnold enjoyed one his more productive games of the season in Week 10, tying a season-high with four catches, but for only 34 yards. Next up is a Seahawks defense allowing the most passing yards in the league, though they are tough on tight ends. Even with a favorable matchup, Arnold isn't a fantasy asset.
outlooksByWeek.12: Arnold did find paydirt in Week 11, but it was on his only reception -- in a game where he saw just two targets. The TE position is not prominent enough in the Arizona offense to consider Arnold for your fantasy squad, even coming out of a game in which he recorded a touchdown.
outlooksByWeek.13: Arnold is clearly running second behind Maxx Williams at tight end at this point. With the Arizona offense utilizing the position as infrequently as it does, he's not going to be an impact player for your lineup any time soon.
outlooksByWeek.14: Arnold continues to run hotter than Maxx Williams at Arizona's TE position, but neither option is seeing enough volume to trust with a spot in your fantasy lineup. Kliff Kingsbury simply does not utilize the position often enough in his offense.
outlooksByWeek.15: The TE position is not even a full-time starting gig in the Arizona offense, but merely a rotational option with limited passing-game involvement. Arnold is the better pick for fantasy given his scoring upside and target share, but it's not nearly enough to consider him for your lineups this week against the Eagles.
outlooksByWeek.16: Maxx Williams could be out for the Cardinals in Week 16, which would open up more opportunities for Arnold. However, it's not like Williams was stealing a ton of looks. Rather, the Cardinals simply don't utilize their tight ends often enough for any of them to have fantasy value. Look elsewhere for Week 16.
outlooksByWeek.17: Not one of the Arizona tight ends are seeing full-time snaps lately, so even when one pops up with a catch or two, their upside is limited. Arnold is not a recommended starter for Week 17 lineups.

outlooksByWeek.1: A third-round selection of New England in the draft, this hulking UCLA product profiles more as a versatile blocking tight end than a fantasy-friendly "move" tight end. The Dolphins were right around league average in defending tight ends last season, which means there is no compelling reason to roster him ahead of this division meeting.

player.seasonOutlook: New England selected Asiasi with a third-round pick during April's draft. Asiasi is one of the heaviest tight ends in this year's class at 6-foot-3, 257 pounds, but he has decent pass-catching chops and actually aligned in the slot on 59% of his snaps at UCLA last season. Asiasi is a good athlete with decent speed (4.73 40-yard dash) who has served as both a reliable target (one drop on 69 targets last season) and downfield playmaker (10.8 aDOT). Also a capable blocker, Asiasi very well could emerge as New England's eventual top tight end. In 2020, he'll compete with Matt LaCosse, Ryan Izzo and Dalton Keene and is well off the fantasy radar.

outlooksByWeek.4: With the favor of the coaching staff, Ballage could see more work in this matchup given how productive he was on limited touches in Week 3. Denver is allowing 4.2 yards per carry to backs, but Ballage's role is still too limited to trust.
outlooksByWeek.10: Serving as the team's primary rushing back once Justin Jackson went down on the first series this past week, Ballage rumbled for a nice 69 yards on 15 carries with a touchdown. If Jackson isn't able to go this week against Miami's porous rush defense, Ballage makes for a helpful plug-and-play option.
outlooksByWeek.11: Suddenly the featured back for the Chargers, Ballage handled a bountiful workload this past week that included 23 touches for 102 scrimmage yards. With Justin Jackson sidelined and Josh Kelley fading, Ballage is poised to enjoy a strong week facing his former team. It helps his case as a strong RB2 play that the Jets have yielded roughly 27 fantasy points per game to backfields.
outlooksByWeek.12: Netting 3.2 yards per carry and 3.0 yards per target is an almost impressive feat of inefficiency for a back who consumed 23 touches this past week. Ballage makes for a sound flex play or even RB2 candidate if he's still the featured back this week against the Bills, but the potential return of Austin Ekeler is worth tracking.
outlooksByWeek.13: Inactive in Week 12 with injury, Ballage's run as the Chargers' lead back is almost surely over. With Austin Ekeler back in the mix, Ballage is likely isolated to part-time early-down duties this week against New England.
outlooksByWeek.14: The Chargers seem to trust Ballage as a key early-down option, as he saw seven carries to Austin Ekeler's eight in Week 13. This role doesn't really translate to fantasy fun, however, with Ekeler consuming nearly all of the passing usage from the backfield while also proving more effective in the red zone. The Falcons have been solid against the run this year, confirming Ballage as a poor option this week.
outlooksByWeek.15: Averaging nine touches the past two games as the Chargers' complementary tailback, Ballage's lack of receiving usage means he's not a worthy fantasy play against the Raiders this week.
outlooksByWeek.16: Grinding out a late-career Jerome Bettis type of line that included 1.4 yards per touch but some rewarding work around the goal line. There's no reason to roster Ballage ahead of this upcoming tilt with Denver given his lack of efficiency with the ball.
outlooksByWeek.17: Averaging just 3.5 yards per rush this past week and mostly isolated to early-down work, Ballage isn't a viable fantasy play even with the Chiefs sitting their key defensive playmakers this week.

outlooksByWeek.1: If rookie Antonio Gibson can't handle the every-down duties for Washington at running back, Barber is waiting to pick up the slack and carry the load. The former Buccaneer averaged only 3.1 YPC a season ago but could see volume in the Washington offense if the first-year player ahead of him stumbles. Keep an eye on him, but he's not worth a speculative start in Week 1.
outlooksByWeek.2: Barber enjoyed a team-high 17 carries, gaining a sad 29 yards. However, two of his touches resulted in short TD runs, solidifying his role as Washington’s goal-line back. The club should be able to move the ball in Week 2 against the Cardinals defense. However, since Barber is so reliant on finding paydirt for fantasy points, there are much better options to be found out there, especially in PPR leagues.
outlooksByWeek.3: After playing the role of fantasy spoiler in Week 1 with two rushing touchdowns, Barber was on the field for just one offensive play in Week 2. Game flow may have dictated the limited usage, but with touchdowns impossible to predict, Barber cuts right to the waiver wire.
outlooksByWeek.4: A pair of rushing scores in the season opener offered some optimisn that Barber would carve out a role in the Washington backfield. However, he's toted the ball just four times combined over the last two games. Time for this Barber to get cut.
outlooksByWeek.5: Barber has all but vanished from Washington's gameplan, seeing the field for just five snaps in Week 4, carrying the ball three times for five yards. If you were holding out hope that Barber would carve out a meaningful role in this offense, it's time to move on.
outlooksByWeek.6: Barber has all but disappeared, seeing just two snaps last week against the Rams.
outlooksByWeek.7: Barber's role in the Washington offense remained limited in Week 6 as he saw just five touches for 10 scrimmage yards against the Giants. His action isn't likely to increase this week facing the Cowboys, relegating the veteran to the fantasy scrap heap.
outlooksByWeek.9: With Washington looking to grind it out against Dallas in Week 7, Barber's 10 carries were his first double-digit effort since Week 1. However, he was held to just 34 yards. That's not nearly enough to make a fantasy difference. There isn't any reason to believe things will be different when Washington takes the field on Sunday, even refreshed as they may well be after their Week 8 bye.
outlooksByWeek.10: Barber was on the field for just one offensive play in Week 9, matching his season low from Week 2. It appears Barber has been shaved from Washington's game plan.
outlooksByWeek.11: After barely seeing the field in Week 9, Barber played on just 10 snaps in Week 10, getting a miniscule two carries for seven yards -- and a catch for seven more. With Antonio Gibson and J.D. McKissic sharing backfield duties, there isn't much left for Barber.
outlooksByWeek.12: This past weekend, Barber saw his most action since Week 7, but it was still good for only 28 yards on eight carries. Barber remains a fantasy afterthought.
outlooksByWeek.13: Everything seemed to land in Barber's favor in Week 12 as he was able to scissor through the Cowboys defense for 57 yards on 11 carries in Washington's win on Thanksgiving. Barber's resurgence was likely a one-off so he's not an option against the much tougher Steelers defense in a Week 13 visit to Pittsburgh.
outlooksByWeek.14: With Antonio Gibson sidelined early in Week 13 due to a foot injury, Barber's 14 carries were his most since way back in Week 1. For the day, Barber gained 23 yards, but his one-yard TD plunge in the third quarter helped spur on "The Football Team" to hand Pittsburgh it's first defeat of the season. Even if Gibson isn't ready to go in Week 14, Barber isn't reliable enough to deploy.
outlooksByWeek.15: Barber was elevated to being Washington's No. 2 running back with Antonio Gibson sidelined in Week 14. He responded with 37 yards on 12 carries, along with two receptions for one yard. This action occured as The Football Team played ball control in the fourth quarter, closing out a eight-point win over San Francisco. Week 15's gameflow is less likely to benefit Barber with the high-scoring Seahawks visiting Washington, keeping him out of the fantasy picture.
outlooksByWeek.16: Even with Antonio Gibson sidelined in Week 15, gameflow limited Barber to just four carries for five yards -- although he did score The Football Team's first touchdown on a one-yard plunge in their loss to the Seahawks. Gibson is questionable for Week 16 but, even if he's still out, Barber's limited activity in Washington's passing game and his TD-dependent numbers render him too risky for fantasy deployment.
outlooksByWeek.17: Barber was on the field for only four plays in Week 16, rushing once for 10 yards. His primary role in Week 17 will be as a cheerleader, with Washington seeking to secure the NFC East crown with a win in Philadelphia.

player.seasonOutlook: Barber signed with Washington following four seasons in Tampa Bay. The 26-year-old will have his hands full finding a consistent role with Antonio Gibson, Bryce Love and J.D. McKissic also in the fold. Although durability and age are major questions for the backs above him, it's unlikely that all will miss enough time for Barber to land on the fantasy radar. An early-down plodder with poor efficiency stats (3.6 YPC, 1.7 YAC, 4.7 YPT), the 26-year-old shouldn't be drafted.

outlooksByWeek.1: Barkley hit the 1,000-yard mark in 2019 in only 13 games, as he was slowed by injuries but still produced at a high level. He chipped in as a receiver as well, and has demonstrated over his first two seasons that he's an every-down contributor who will only be held back by ailments or his team's offense. The Steelers had a top-five run defense last season when it came to stopping opposing backs from scoring fantasy points, but Barkley is matchup-proof. Start him every week.
outlooksByWeek.2: While Barkley’s production was expected to be dampened a bit by running behind a young offensive line, gaining just six yards on 15 carries is obviously excessively low. Luckily, his six catches for 60 yards helped salvage the opener. As most teams do, the Steelers keyed on Barkley throughout Week 1's Monday night affair. Even with a couple of rookie lineman blocking for him, Barkley remains an automatic start with Week 2 offering a less-resistant Bears defense.
outlooksByWeek.3: In a crushing blow to the Giants and fantasy teams alike, Barkley tore his right ACL against the Bears and is out for the season.

player.seasonOutlook: Barkley's 2019 season fell short of lofty expectations, but the 2018 second-overall pick finished strongly and remains an elite fantasy asset. Barkley, who missed three games because of injury, was on the field for 84% of New York's snaps -- about the same as his rookie season (83%) -- when active. His 16.7 carries per game were up slightly from 2018 (16.3), though his targets inexplicably fell from 7.4 to 5.5 per game. Barkley still managed the third-most fantasy points among RBs during his 12 full weeks. We shouldn't count on a big rebound in targets with Jason Garrett running the offense, but Barkley does figure to see more run at the goal line (only seven carries inside the 5 last season). Only Christian McCaffrey is a clear superior fantasy asset to 23-year-old Barkley.
